                                </div>


                                <p class="p1">
                                    After years of expansion through mergers and acquisitions, the American-based company found itself with divisions in a variety of countries, senior executives from over 20 nationalities but no clear vision or sense of espoused cultural identity.<br>
                                    <br>
                                    “It’s a common problem as companies evolve and the personal influence of the founder is diluted,” says Thom Dennis. “Apple is still Steve Jobs. But for how much longer?”<br>
                                    <br>
                                    So when the Phoenix Obsidian team were asked to rejuvenate a customer focus programme for the company, they set out to develop a new approach that took into account the diverse cultural mix of its senior managers and also their different professional backgrounds. Many began their working lives on the oil rigs where work only stopped for meals as there was nothing else to do. This 24/7 work culture created problems when it was transported to their roles on dry land.<br>
                                    <br>
                                    “Colleagues who didn’t come from rigs found it bizarre,” points out Thom. “So there were two separate work cultures on top of the international mix.”<br>
                                    <br>
                                    From the outset, Thom saw the role of the members of his team as those of diplomats. Rather than expect everyone to conform to one style of workshop, they adapted their methods to suit the different national sensibilities they came across. 			</p>	
                                <p>	
                                    “The Americans liked everything upbeat,” he recalls. “But managers from South East Asia, for instance tend to be more reserved and wary of failure. It was important to make sure they never lost face in front of their colleagues.”<br>
                                    <br>
                                    With such a complex blend of nationalities, the temptation was to create a programme to match. But when it came to explaining why managers were losing business to start-up companies, the team decided to keep things simple. They invited a client to tell executives to their faces what it was like being a customer, what was going well and what aspects needed improving.<br>
                                    <br>
                                    “Looking someone in the eye and telling them why the next piece of business might not be coming their way cuts across national boundaries,” Thom reflected.<br>
                                    <br>
                                    They might have raised eyebrows at the United Nations but the team’s down-to-earth style of diplomacy worked wonders. At the end of one session, a manager immediately emailed an angry customer who was refusing to pay a bill to say sorry: “The customer paid a disputed invoice of $4.5m shortly afterwards.”<br>
                                    <br>
                                    Although the Phoenix Obsidian team adapted its techniques to suit the audience, the end result was the same. By the time they finished working with the diverse group, all the senior executives had a clear understanding of what their company stood for and how these positive attributes could be conveyed to customers to secure more business in the future – and as a bonus get a disputed multimillion dollar bill resolved.			</p>
                                <div class="quote">
                                    <span class="1">“</span>I've been meaning to email you and let you know how pleased I was to hear of the success of the workshop. The program really paid off and I know it will continue to improve each time you run it. I'm a firm believer that professionals should continue to run these workshops and I'll do what I can to influence those in charge. Keep up the good work, as you know we need the education, and please pass on my thanks to the team for a job well done!<span class="2">”</span>				<div class="dedicace">
                                        <!--From-->&nbsp;&nbsp;<span>Commissioning Manager</span>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
