                                </div>


                                <p class="p1">
                                    The arrival of an American head of department threatened to disturb the peaceful neutrality inside the Swiss pharmaceutical company’s headquarters. Despite overseeing a team made up of Swiss nationals who all spoke French, the new executive pushed for the meeting to take place in English.<br>
                                    <br>
                                    “He argued that English was the company’s language,” says Thom Dennis “But we took a more pragmatic view.”<br>
                                    <br>
                                    For the Phoenix Obsidian team, solidarity is vital to changing a company’s culture and improving the effectiveness of its people. Where possible, senior management should seek to persuade an organisation that transformation is needed, rather than impose change from above. The team’s mantra is ‘Pace and Lead’.<br>
                                    <br>
                                    “You have to be sensitive to the people who work in a company. After all, they are the key to its success. It’s important you introduce change at a pace that brings people on-board whilst creating the necessary momentum. The pace normally ends up being very fast, but your efforts will be wasted if you lose everyone at the beginning.”<br>
                                    <br>
                                    At this pharmaceutical company, the team were faced with a department of what they called “proud French speakers”. The team ethos suggested that conducting workshops solely in English would be a grave mistake.			</p>	
                                <p>	
                                    “The new manager needed to gain their trust. Forcing everyone to use English from the start would have been insensitive and provocative.”<br>
                                    <br>
                                    So when the American executive came to deliver his all-important ‘vision’ speech to his new department, the team advised him to use two PowerPoint presentations: one in English, one in French. The team also brought forward a French-speaking associate who facilitated the team-building workshops.<br>
                                    <br>
                                    When the employees saw the French version of his speech, the atmosphere in the department improved immediately. The Alpine chill that threatened to hamper a constructive dialogue between the executive and his colleagues soon began to thaw as they realised he was willing to respect their sensitivities and meet them half-way.<br>
                                    <br>
                                    “The minute that French presentation came on the screen, everyone relaxed. It’s the first time I’ve ever seen a room of people smile at a PowerPoint.”			</p>
                                <div class="quote">
                                    <span class="1">“</span>I appreciated your holding out for the dual language presentation. It made things go much slower than was my natural style but that turned out to have  its advantages and it was clear that people were following me when I feared this was going to be a battle. Thanks very much for giving us a new perspective.<span class="2">”</span>				<div class="dedicace">
                                        <!--From-->&nbsp;&nbsp;<span>Department Head</span>
                                    </div>
