                                                <p class="p1">
                                                        The arrival of a new CEO was the perfect opportunity to refresh the company from top to bottom. Although its products were innovative, including drug treatments for ulcers and asthma, the company’s culture had grown stale. The core problem was a senior management team, most of whose roles hadn’t changed for a considerable time.
                                                        <br /><br />
                                                        Although executives remaining in the same position for many years used to be common in France, Thom believes it resulted in a culture where timely decisions were not made, risks were avoided and young talent was blocked from the top, making retention difficult. Fortunately for the company, the new CEO saw the roots of the problem and had the vision to "shake things up". So, soon after arriving in his post, he invited Phoenix Obsidian to work with him to change the pharmaceutical company’s culture from the top down.
                                                        <br /><br />
                                                        The key challenge for Thom and his French associate Patricia Bouvard was to give senior managers the confidence to behave differently. Simply telling everyone below them that things were going to be different wouldn’t bring about the transformation the company clearly needed.
                                                        <br /><br />
                                                        "You can’t impose a new vision and values on people," says Thom. "They need to see the new behaviours being lived every day by senior management. When that happens, the vision and particularly the values can cascade all the way down the organisation."
                                                        <br /><br />
                                                        To change the behaviour of the senior team, Thom and Patricia used a method that is based on masks representing different characters from the 14th century Italian theatre, the Commedia dell’Arte. The personality of each character was identified by the group of executives and then they were invited to try on the mask they felt best represented their own character. Next, they were encouraged to try a different character that was nothing like them. The result, says Patricia, was amazing.
                                                </p>	
                                                <p>	
                                                        "The masks changed the way that people looked at each other. The team could then understand and recognise how people are different and they learnt to be more tolerant of each other. This leads to more adaptability and flexibility. You recognise how you look at people and how they look at you", said the CEO. 
                                                        <br /><br />
                                                        "People lost their inhibitions very quickly. For the first time in a long time, the executives began to open up and talk honestly about the company. Those historic masks gave them a new burst of life."
                                                        <br /><br />
                                                        For over two years, Phoenix Obsidian continued to work with the company. Over that time, the company’s whole culture was transformed as everyone from senior managers to cleaners, developed new ways of expressing themselves and dealing with difficult issues – thanks in no small part to the seven main characters from the Commedia dell’Arte.
                                                        <br /><br />
                                                        "The masks helped create a new language while the new culture was being introduced," reflects Thom. "Executives started to say, for instance: 'You're acting like a real Pulcinella'. It made resolving conflicts easier and less personal. Everything began to flow again."
                                                        <br /><br />
                                                        Not everyone experienced the cultural shift first-hand. The company’s all-important sales team of 150 were constantly travelling around France. To make sure they also benefited from the newly energised organisation, the CEO invited Thom and his team to Cannes where the sales people worked together and met with new eyes the executive team they had once considered cold, stuffy and remote.
                                                        <br /><br />
                                                        To break down barriers built up over many years, Thom gave the salespeople Harry Potter Lego sets to play with. Before long, old misgivings were replaced with camaraderie and miniature versions of Hogwarts.
                                                        <br /><br />
                                                        "I wanted to encourage everyone to have fun building things together,” he says. “As you expect from Harry Potter, it worked like magic."
                                                        <br /><br />
                                                        Not long after the successful transformation of the company, and Thom and Patricia had packed away their masks and wands, the company was taken over by a large multinational.
                        
                                                        <div class="dedicace">
                                                                From&nbsp;&nbsp;<span>Yves Charpentier</span>
                                                        </div>
                                                </p>
